  "text": "Supply price per unit (P): This is the FOB (Freight on Board) unit price at which the supplier will deliver the component to the buyer for the contract life. No quantity discount is applied to this price. Penalties will be imposed on this price when the buyer places orders outside the limits specified in the supply contract. Minimum order quantity (Qmin): The buyer commits with the supplier to a minimum order quantity i.e. the buyer is made long term commitment with the supplier. When orders are below the minimum quantity then a price penalty is imposed. The buyer also has option not to order when demand is dropped and there is no penalty for this. Order quantity reduction penalty (β): This is the maximum penalty paid by the buyer when the order quantity is below Qmin. The penalty is linearly graded as a function of the order quantity i.e. if the order quantity is Q in any period, the quantity penalty is β(Qmin-Q)/Qmin when Qlost<Q<Qmin. Here, Qlost is the demand level below which management decides to loss the current sales rather than pay the order quantity penalty. The penalty β protects both the buyer and supplier, and must therefore be carefully negotiated. The above mentioned three parameters are determined as part of the supplier-buyer negotiations and supply flexibility in the relationship. When multiple suppliers are available, the buyer must select the one which provides the best flexibility and least expected supply cost [CITATION_1] . ",
